<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> put a question to someone • put someone to the question</xh5><p> <i>put a question to someone—</i>ask a person about smth.: I have been trying to <u>put this question to</u> the general for the last year or two—even succeeding in planting it in the <i>Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists</i>.</p><p> <i>put someone to the question</i>—(dated) subject smb. to torture as a means of obtaining confession: “Did he confess his wizardry when you <u>put him to the question</u>?” “Alas, no,” replied Maître Jacques.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>call someone into question</b>—doubt the qualifications or value of a person: Because of her poor record, we were forced to <u>call Dr. Jones into question</u>.</p> </entry>
